Perioperative smoking cessation.

de Hoyos A(1), Southard C, DeCamp MM.

Author information:
(1)Division of Thoracic Surgery, Northwestern Memorial Hospital, Northwestern 
University Feinberg School of Medicine, 676 North Saint Clair Street, Suite 650, 
Chicago, IL 60611, USA. mdecamp@nmh.org

Smoking is the leading cause of preventable death worldwide. Smoking cessation 
programs that include counseling and pharmacotherapy have been proved to be 
effective in achieving long-standing abstinence. Smoking cessation is associated 
with significant improvements in quality of life, mortality, life expectancy, 
and postsurgical complication rates. Contrary to general belief, smoking 
cessation close to the time of elective surgery does not increase the risk of 
pulmonary complications. Longer-term quit rates are generally higher in cohorts 
who quit in anticipation of surgery compared with those quitting for general 
health considerations. A team approach and adherence to the guidelines for 
smoking cessation improves long-term chances of success.

